			<h2 class="post-title"><a href="http://www.theabsurdreport.com/2011/the-effects-of-rising-capital-gains-taxes-on-actual-tax-receipts-by-rob-johnson/" rel="bookmark" title="Permanent Link: The Effects Of Rising Capital Gains Taxes On Actual Tax Receipts by Rob Johnson">The Effects Of Rising Capital Gains Taxes On Actual Tax Receipts by Rob Johnson</a></h2>
			<p class="post-info"><em class="user"><a href="http://www.theabsurdreport.com/author/the-bear/" title="Posts by The Bear" rel="author">The Bear</a></em> on <em>Sep 22 2011 at 7:00 am</em> | Filed under: <em><a href="http://www.theabsurdreport.com/category/economy/" title="View all posts in Economy" rel="category tag">Economy</a>, <a href="http://www.theabsurdreport.com/category/politics/" title="View all posts in Politics" rel="category tag">Politics</a>, <a href="http://www.theabsurdreport.com/category/taxes/" title="View all posts in Taxes" rel="category tag">Taxes</a></em> </p>
			<div class="post-content">
				<p>President Obama yesterday insisted that Congress enact a $1.5 Trillion tax increase on the well-to-do. Although he wasn&#8217;t specific about what he meant, he can only be referring to raising the Capital Gains Tax rate.</p>
<p>In 2009, the UK was considering raising their Capital Gains Tax rate from 18% to 28%, which they did in 2010 for all but the bottom income earners. During the debate on raising the tax, a study was conducted by the Adam Smith Institute analyzing the numbers in the US.</p>
<p>Capital gains tax rates in the USA have changed considerably up and down in recent years and decades and provide a rich seam of data with which one can come to solid conclusions on the revenue effects of such changes. One can be sure that President Obama has not seen, nor does he likely care to see, what history has shown.</p>
<p><a href="http://www.theabsurdreport.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/Capital-Gains-Rates.jpg"><img src="http://www.theabsurdreport.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/Capital-Gains-Rates.jpg" alt="" title="Capital Gains Rates" width="603" height="438" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-41484" /></a></p>
<p><strong>The pattern shows that every time the capital gains tax has been cut, capital gains tax revenues have risen. Every time the capital gains tax has been raised, capital gains tax revenues have fallen. The following are some clear examples:</strong><br />
[...]<br />
All of the data were summarized in an important piece of research by Professor Paul D. Evans of Ohio State University, who looked at how taxpayers might respond to an increase in the capital gains rate, using taxpayer data from the most recent available years at the time of his study.</p>
<p>In his study, The Relationship Between Realized Capital Gains and Their Marginal Rate of Taxation, 1976-2004, Evans found that at current US tax rates, a 1 percentage point reduction in the marginal tax rates on capital gains might trigger a 10.32 percent increase in realized capital gains. Behavior in recent years is broadly similar to that found in earlier studies, so this likely holds true for 2011.</p>
<p>He found that raising the US capital gains tax rate from the current 15% <strong>would reduce federal capital gains tax revenue</strong> and that additional revenue would be lost from other parts of the income tax and from other federal taxes due to reduced investment, employment, and income. <strong>He found that the optimal capital gains tax rate to maximize public welfare, and to help the federal budget, is closer to if not zero.</strong></p>
<p>Furthermore, the gains in tax receipts following the reduction of the CGT rate to 15% in 2003 were not expected by the Congressional Budget Office and the Joint Committee on Taxation, which officially score tax changes. The graph below compares actual capital gains revenues with the forecasts made when the tax cut was proposed:</p>
<p><a href="http://www.640wgst.com/pages/RobJohnson.html?article=9132200#.Tnh3eis5vXE.email">Read more from <em>The Talk of Atlanta </em></a></p>
<p><strong>SideBear:</strong> What is misleading about this &#8220;Buffet Rule&#8221; debate (class envy) is the dollars that are used to invest in stocks etc. has already been taxed already at 35% (pick a rate) and the Capital Gain taxes is a second tax on the same money and when you add ins State and Local taxes, the money is being taxed at a rate well above 50%. </p>
<p>This is the part of the story that Warren Buffet left out.</p>
