	<h3 id="comments">7 Responses to &#8220;The Effects Of Rising Capital Gains Taxes On Actual Tax Receipts by Rob Johnson&#8221;</h3> 

	<ol class="commentlist">
						<li class="alt " id="comment-678596">
			<div class="cmtinfo"><em> on 25 Feb 2012 at 12:59 am <small class="commentmetadata"><a href="#comment-678596" title=""><span class="commentnum">1</span></a></small></em><cite>mediajammer</cite></div>
						
			<p>Your conclusions are absurd. If the government tells me that long-term capital gains taxes are going to rise next year, I&#8217;m going to take my profit while the tax rate is lower. I&#8217;m sure everyone else is going to as well. This is going to mean a big rise in revenues from capital gains. And you completely mis-understand the &#8216;Buffet Rule&#8217;. I&#8217;m not going to be taxed a second time on the money I&#8217;ve already been taxed on, I&#8217;m only getting taxed on my profit. Which is a lot less than the tax rate on my day job, which costs me more than double the tax rate. Not only that, but I really don&#8217;t have to work much to make that profit; my capital is working for me! Kinda like owning slaves!</p>
						
		</li>

	
					<li class=" " id="comment-678597">
			<div class="cmtinfo"><em> on 25 Feb 2012 at 7:53 am <small class="commentmetadata"><a href="#comment-678597" title=""><span class="commentnum">2</span></a></small></em><cite>DocNeaves</cite></div>
						
			<p>&#8220;Your conclusions are absurd.&#8221;</p>
<p>I agree, your conclusions are absurd.</p>
<p>&#8220;If the government tells me that long-term capital gains taxes are going to rise next year, I’m going to take my profit while the tax rate is lower. I’m sure everyone else is going to as well.&#8221;</p>
<p>No, they are not.  First of all, this implies you know absolutely nothing about investing, since people don&#8217;t move money in and out of investments on a whim, much less on a minor thing like a little more or less tax.  Most of those investments are time sensitive, or real estate, neither of which sells on the next bid like stocks.  And even stock sales have to be carefully considered when you have that much money.  Secondly, the calculations have to be made, and not everyone will do the same thing.  Each will be in a different situation, each will be affected differently, and each will have a different &#8216;best move&#8217; to make.  Third, this simple assumption completely ignores that you&#8217;re just moving SOME revenue from next year&#8217;s higher rate (money you didn&#8217;t get, sort of like selling it this year for ten bucks instead of waiting and selling it next year for twelve) into this year, and next year will come up short.  It will wash in the end.</p>
<p>&#8220;And you completely mis-understand the ‘Buffet Rule’. I’m not going to be taxed a second time on the money I’ve already been taxed on, I’m only getting taxed on my profit.&#8221;</p>
<p>You have already paid a tax on that corporate profit.  Your tax is the second one applied.  It is YOU who misunderstand something so vague as the Buffet Rule (since it can be tweaked and changed without actually admitting that it was, not including the different ways to interpret what&#8217;s there already, it&#8217;s hardly measurable or comparable to actual tax rates).  Not only that, you liberal/socialists always leave out the part where taxes go up, tax revenue goes down.  It&#8217;s not a zero sum game.  The money just doesn&#8217;t get invested, or gets invested somewhere else.</p>
<p>&#8220;Which is a lot less than the tax rate on my day job&#8221;</p>
<p>Um, I&#8217;m going to have to go with liar here, unless you make a boatload of money.  Capital gains rates are twenty to twenty eight percent.  In the top tax brackets, you&#8217;re only paying thirty five, that&#8217;s just not a lot more than the tax rate.  Chances are, with deductions and all, you&#8217;re actually only paying about fifteen to twenty, which is less than the capital gains tax rates being bandied about by anyone, much less Buffet.</p>
<p>&#8220;which costs me more than double the tax rate.&#8221;</p>
<p>You&#8217;re not very clear here.  What exactly costs you twice the tax rate?  And which tax rate, the capital gains, or your current income tax bracket?  And, you&#8217;re not clear on which bracket you&#8217;re in, you should state this just to reduce confusion.</p>
<p>&#8220;Not only that, but I really don’t have to work much to make that profit; my capital is working for me! Kinda like owning slaves!&#8221;</p>
<p>This is called capitalism.  They taught it in my school.  Where did you go?  Your money could have been invested in real estate, which gets more valuable, and then you sell it.  Where did you own slaves?  What law did you break?  Which human did you demean or dehumanize in the ownership of your land?  How can you equate making profit with owning slaves?  I think you are simply repeating Marxist crap, and I doubt that you even have a job, much less one who would pay taxes.</p>
						
		</li>

	
					<li class="alt " id="comment-678599">
