			<p>The comment about slaves is that you took your cash, bought some, and now they earn you money. Just like the stock market. I would not have a wash selling a stock this year in a low long term-capital gains tax structure vs. next year in a higher capital gains tax. To be clear, if I get taxed $15 on the sale of my $100 stock this year, and $20 if I sell next year, I have a big incentive to take my profit this year. It&#8217;s that simple.  </p>
<p>&#8220;You&#8217;ve already paid a tax on that corporate profit&#8221;. No, the corporation I invested in paid a tax. If I earn $20,000, I pay taxes on that, and if I then hire someone and pay them $20,000, they pay a tax on that. They didn&#8217;t pay my taxes, and I didn&#8217;t pay theirs. The money goes around, and it gets earned (and taxed) multiple times year year.</p>
<p>I was unclear about the different tax rates; when I make a long-term capital gains sale, I pay 15% tax. If I earn that same money as wages, I pay maybe 35%. I might indeed get a deduction that reduces my taxes, but that would be the same if it were capital gains or wages. But I&#8217;ve got alot more deductions available for my capital gains profits, as I can deduct expenses and losses, which I really can&#8217;t with wages. </p>
<p>&#8221; I think you are simply repeating Marxist crap, and I doubt that you even have a job, much less one who would pay taxes.&#8221;</p>
<p>I think you&#8217;re spouting some warmed over slogans worthy of Senator McCarthy. If you actually have a job, it&#8217;s because someone owes you father a favor, not because you can think your way through any problem with logic. You can&#8217;t.</p>
						
