					<li class=" " id="comment-678600">
			<div class="cmtinfo"><em> on 26 Feb 2012 at 8:58 am <small class="commentmetadata"><a href="#comment-678600" title=""><span class="commentnum">4</span></a></small></em><cite>DocNeaves</cite></div>
						
			<p>&#8220;The comment about slaves is that you took your cash, bought some, and now they earn you money. Just like the stock market.&#8221;</p>
<p>Okay, you&#8217;re a Marxist, we get it.  You think owning a business is like slavery.  But what&#8217;s your option?  For the state to own the business and be the slave owner?  Tell me, do you make a profit at your job?  I think you do, so that makes you a slave owner as well.</p>
<p>&#8220;I would not have a wash selling a stock this year in a low long term-capital gains tax structure vs. next year in a higher capital gains tax. To be clear, if I get taxed $15 on the sale of my $100 stock this year, and $20 if I sell next year, I have a big incentive to take my profit this year. It’s that simple.&#8221;</p>
<p>Actually, you have little incentive to sell this year.  You&#8217;re only talking about a five percent difference.  Stock strade up and down that much in a week.  You would hold or sell the stock depending upon your investment decisions.  But of course, you don&#8217;t know anything about this, because you&#8217;re a Marxist.  You really should learn about something before you condemn it, instead of just repeating your professor&#8217;s pap.</p>
<p>“You’ve already paid a tax on that corporate profit”. No, the corporation I invested in paid a tax.&#8221;</p>
<p>Wow, you agree with me and still think you&#8217;re disagreeing with me.  A hundred dollars profit was taxed at whatever rate, then taxed again when it was distributed to you.  If you&#8217;re too stupid to understand this, please, just stop talking.</p>
<p>&#8220;If I earn $20,000, I pay taxes on that, and if I then hire someone and pay them $20,000, they pay a tax on that. They didn’t pay my taxes, and I didn’t pay theirs. The money goes around, and it gets earned (and taxed) multiple times year year.&#8221;</p>
<p>Keynsian bullshit.  If you earn twenty thousand, you pay taxes.  You then hire someone, how are you going to pay them twenty grand?  You have twenty grand minus the taxes.  Then you pay him whatever you have left, he pays taxes, eventually, the pool shrinks.  Got it?  That money is money that WOULD have been spent in the local economy, by you, by spending the whole twenty grand to hire someone, who could then do it again, and again, and again.  Instead, the money goes to taxes, which is more wasteful than any spending category, especially because of the corruption and waste.  You spending a dollar or saving a dollar gets a dollar&#8217;s worth of spending or saving, the government gets that dollar minus corruption and waste, which always goes to rich people, or at least, they&#8217;re rich once they get their graft.</p>
<p>&#8220;I was unclear about the different tax rates; when I make a long-term capital gains sale, I pay 15% tax. If I earn that same money as wages, I pay maybe 35%. I might indeed get a deduction that reduces my taxes, but that would be the same if it were capital gains or wages. But I’ve got alot more deductions available for my capital gains profits, as I can deduct expenses and losses, which I really can’t with wages.&#8221;</p>
<p>Wow, where to begin.  Yes, you can deduct expenses and losses with wages, I&#8217;ve done it every year I worked, unless they were too small to worry about.  Capital gains is treated differently than income, and even with the different tax rates, you&#8217;re still talking about a very small difference, a few percentage points of the price of the stock, an insignificant amount in overall consideration of whether to buy and sell.  Again, you demonstrate an amazing ignorance of all things capitalism, including how the stock market and the tax system works.</p>
<p>” I think you are simply repeating Marxist crap, and I doubt that you even have a job, much less one who would pay taxes.”</p>
<p>I think you’re spouting some warmed over slogans worthy of Senator McCarthy.&#8221;</p>
<p>I am stating facts.  Just because they have to be repeated ad infinitum to respond to your lies doesn&#8217;t make them untrue or &#8220;warmed over&#8221; anything.  And Senator McCarthy was right about ninety five percent of the people he accused, so be careful who you associate me with, the slander job on McCarthy is coming unravelled as time goes on.</p>
<p>&#8220;If you actually have a job, it’s because someone owes you father a favor, not because you can think your way through any problem with logic. You can’t.&#8221;</p>
<p>This is called a Non-Sequitur.  If I have a job, it&#8217;s because I have a skill, not because I can &#8220;think my way through any problem&#8221;.  Of course, that skill should be handy in any job, but it&#8217;s not required in many of them, especially low-skilled labor jobs.  The second half is that you have not demonstrated any reason why I don&#8217;t have logic, or why my father being owed a favor got me my job.  All of which you make up from whole cloth.  Together, these are called a strawman argument.  You string several things, assumptions, together with the final assumption being that they are relevant to each other, when, besides being false, they are not connected anywhere except in your fevered mind.  I have shown where YOUR logic has failed or is not present.  Show me where mine has failed.</p>
						
		</li>

	
					<li class="alt " id="comment-678716">
			<div class="cmtinfo"><em> on 28 Mar 2012 at 11:16 am <small class="commentmetadata"><a href="#comment-678716" title=""><span class="commentnum">5</span></a></small></em><cite>stanooch</cite></div>
						
			<p>DocNeaves said:<br />
“Capital gains rates are twenty to twenty eight percent.”</p>
<p>From BankRate.com:<br />
“Currently, capital gains are at historic lows. Some taxpayers in the two lowest tax brackets could end up without any capital gains tax bill. That&#8217;s right, zero capital gains for some filers.</p>
<p>“Others will face tax rates of just 5 percent. Most investors will see their gains taxed at 15 percent. And 25 percent and 28 percent rates apply in special circumstances.</p>
<p>“A rate of 25 percent applies to part of the gain from selling real estate you depreciated. Basically this keeps you from getting a double tax break. The Internal Revenue Service first wants to recapture some of the tax breaks you&#8217;ve been getting via depreciation throughout the years.</p>
<p>“If you realized a gain from qualified small-business stock that you held more than five years, you generally can exclude one-half of your gain from income. The remainder is taxed at a 28 percent rate.</p>
<p>“If your gains came from collectibles rather than a business sale, you&#8217;ll still pay the 28 percent rate.”<br />
 <a href="http://www.bankrate.com/finance/money-guides/capital-gains-tax-rates-1.aspx" rel="nofollow">http://www.bankrate.com/finance/money-guides/capital-gains-tax-rates-1.aspx</a></p>
<p>DocNeaves said:<br />
“ ‘If I earn $20,000, I pay taxes on that, and if I then hire someone and pay them $20,000, they pay a tax on that. They didn’t pay my taxes, and I didn’t pay theirs. The money goes around, and it gets earned (and taxed) multiple times year year.’</p>
<p>“Keynsian bullshit. If you earn twenty thousand, you pay taxes. You then hire someone, how are you going to pay them twenty grand? You have twenty grand minus the taxes. Then you pay him whatever you have left, he pays taxes, eventually, the pool shrinks. Got it?”</p>
<p>First, if you earn twenty thousand, you aren’t going to hire anyone you will pay twenty thousand – except in extreme emergency. And even then it will require borrowing. </p>
<p>Second, usually if you pay anyone that much in one year, you are probably much better off than twenty grand a year, and the reason you are paying him anything falls into one of three groups:</p>
<p>1. It is something you don’t want to do yourself (example: gardener, cook, etc.).<br />
2. It is something you don’t know how to do yourself (auto mechanic).<br />
3. You, as an employer, are paying him twenty thousand a year because he, as an employee, adds considerably more to your income than you pay him (you own a restaurant and he is on wait staff).</p>
<p>DocNeaves said:<br />
“[E]ventually, the pool shrinks.”</p>
<p>Yet in your first post, you said, “It’s not a zero sum game.” And you are right: It’s not. </p>
<p>In the restaurant example, other people, because of this other person’s labor, are bringing much more cash into your world than you are paying out to him. Twenty thousand a year works out to roughly $385 per week. If he works five six-hour nights a week, you fork over to him $77 for serving up, say, $500 worth of food.</p>
<p>Now that is capitalism. You have up-front costs (labor) for which he produces more value than you are paying him for (customers’ tab) and you keep the rest. Marx called it “surplus value.”</p>
<p>All Marx really did was examine capitalism and point out how people got rich by paying those whose labor made them rich only the minimum of what they would be willing to work for. The rest, except for some certain other expenses, is where the profit comes from: The production of value to you that you didn&#8217;t pay out to the one who actually produced it.</p>
						
		</li>

	
					<li class=" " id="comment-678717">
			<div class="cmtinfo"><em> on 28 Mar 2012 at 2:13 pm <small class="commentmetadata"><a href="#comment-678717" title=""><span class="commentnum">6</span></a></small></em><cite>DocNeaves</cite></div>
						
			<p>Sorry, I didn&#8217;t allow for special situations and deductions.  I was talking about the rates themselves, which you have proven accurate.  Thanks for proving me right.</p>
<p>As to the second part, we were talking in simple terms, only allowing for the cash flow.  If you want to take all of that other into consideration, fine, but it still doesn&#8217;t change anything, just muddies the waters.  So, in two tries, you&#8217;ve agreed with me, and mumbled.  Not a good start to a rebuttal.</p>
<p>But here&#8217;s where you really get lost:</p>
<p>“[E]ventually, the pool shrinks.”</p>
<p>Yet in your first post, you said, “It’s not a zero sum game.” And you are right: It’s not. </p>
<p>What was meant by &#8220;not a zero sum game&#8221; is that when you raise taxes by ten percent, you won&#8217;t get ten percent increases, because there will be considerable revenue lost from tax avoidance.  Tax REITs, and people will invest in them less, causing a net loss in revenues.  Of course, you don&#8217;t understand this, and are trying to take any of my words to use against me, so you take it out of context in this next part:</p>
<p>&#8220;In the restaurant example, other people, because of this other person’s labor, are bringing much more cash into your world than you are paying out to him. Twenty thousand a year works out to roughly $385 per week. If he works five six-hour nights a week, you fork over to him $77 for serving up, say, $500 worth of food.&#8221;</p>
<p>That extra value comes not just from his labor, but also from the purchase of the food, the labor of the guy who cooked it, the labor of the cleaning staff, the cost of the building, and the cost of investing in it in the first place.  You would like to say we&#8217;re stealing from that waiter, but that&#8217;s because you are a whiny little marxist.  If you were to admit reality, you would not invest a hundred grand in a restaurant, not knowing if you&#8217;ll make money or not, only to have ANY profit you make seized, distributed amongst those whose wages were guaranteed.  Why?  Because you worship Marxism, the lie told hundreds of years ago, that promises you that you can have a free lunch.</p>
<p>&#8220;Now that is capitalism. You have up-front costs (labor) for which he produces more value than you are paying him for (customers’ tab) and you keep the rest. Marx called it “surplus value.”</p>
<p>Marx lied.  It&#8217;s called profit, and it comes from much more than that worker&#8217;s labor.</p>
<p>&#8220;All Marx really did was examine capitalism and point out how people got rich by paying those whose labor made them rich only the minimum of what they would be willing to work for. The rest, except for some certain other expenses, is where the profit comes from: The production of value to you that you didn’t pay out to the one who actually produced it.&#8221;</p>
<p>Again, he lies.  What about the profit owed to you for investing your money?  The laboring had no risk, he worked, and got paid.  The person who risked their money should get paid, too.  But of course, you want to sit around and do nothing, which means you can&#8217;t get paid what your worth or you&#8217;d get nothing.</p>
<p>If you think that you are right, then do this.  Find a worker who is out of a job.  Tell him to produce something, without giving him any specific ideas, plans or drawings, or even specific items to make, and give him no money, tools, or materials.  Let&#8217;s see what he makes, how much he sells it for, and how much is left over when he&#8217;s done.</p>
<p>I&#8217;m betting he&#8217;ll just starve.</p>
<p>Because anyone who believes in Marx is a moron incapable of rational thought.</p>
						
		</li>

	
					<li class="alt " id="comment-678718">
			<div class="cmtinfo"><em> on 28 Mar 2012 at 2:27 pm <small class="commentmetadata"><a href="#comment-678718" title=""><span class="commentnum">7</span></a></small></em><cite>DocNeaves</cite></div>
						
			<p>Just curious&#8230;.you DID know that Marx and Engels were paid to write that crap, right?  Communism, socialism, that was invented whole cloth by the Rothschilds and the World Banking group, in order to repress people and own their money.  You really should read about it.  The check Rothschild wrote Marx is supposedly in a museum in England somewhere.  Imagine, an entire socio-economic system devised for the sole purpose of taking over the world.  Whoda thunk it.</p>
						
		</li>

	
	
	</ol>

